Abstract: 
\series default
The spread of COVID-19 has forced governments to impose restrictions on
 the mobility of citizens' to minimize the risk of infection.
 This has led researchers and several news media to speculate about whether
 working remotely will be the new normal.
 In this project, we scrape data from job postings published to the Danish
 jobportal Jobindex to 
\shape italic
investigate the development of remote work in Denmark over the period 2010-2020
\shape default
.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We explore and characterize the development both overall and across different
 job categories and geographical areas.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\series bold
LISBETH.
 
\series default
The descriptive analysis confirms, that the option of working remotely is
 becoming increasingly available, and global pandemic seems to have created
 a wave for workplaces to ride on with.
 The potential for remote work is dependant on the composition of the labour
 market and the skill level of the labor force, and may also require workplaces
 to formalize policies or guidelines for remote work to be a success in
 the long run.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spread of COVID-19 has forced governments to impose restrictions on
 the mobility of citizens' to minimize the risk of infection.
 This has led researchers and several news media to speculate about whether
 working remotely will be the new normal.
 Although the widespread technological development within portable devices
 and online cloud-sharing has long been predicted to transform the modern
 workplace, no one had foreseen the sudden need for remote work, that followed
 from the outbreak of COVID-19.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
smallskip
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this project, we use data from job postings to 
\shape italic
investigate the development of remote work in Denmark over the period 2010-2020
\shape default
.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We explore and characterize the development both overall and across different
 job categories and geographical areas.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\series bold
LISBETH In light of the COVID-19 pandemic, we characterize the current state
 of remote work in Danmark and forecast the counterfactual of the pandemic
 using machine learning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
smallskip
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We collect the data on the period 2010-2020 by scraping the Danish jobportal
 Jobindex for job postings containing one or more words related to remote
 work from a list defined by ourselves.
 The data trends are explored descriptively and using text analysis.

\series bold
 LISBETH Further, we use a subset of the dataset from 2010-2019 to forecast
 the counterfactual....Forecast! The model is based on time series data and
 is cross-validated using different training and testing data.
 The prediction reveal the development in the remote labour market that
 we could have expected without the outbreak of COVID-19.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
smallskip
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While COVID-19 has led to a renewed interest in the remote labour market,
 the topic has been studied before.
 A recent study by Dingel & Neiman (2020)
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dingel, J and B Neiman (2020), “How Many Jobs Can be Done at Home?”, Covid
 Economics: Vetted and Real-Time Papers 1: 16-24.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 explores the potential of remote working by creating a classification measure
 from the O*NET survey, that estimates the extend to which an occupation
 can be performed entirely from home.
 The authors estimate, that 37 pct.
 of US jobs can plausibly be performed from home, including most jobs in
 finance, corporate management, and professional and scientific services.
 On the other hand very few jobs in agriculture, hotels and restaurants,
 or retail could be converted to remote.
 The authors also note, that there is a significant variation across geographica
l areas, depending on the types of jobs and skills of workers in the specific
 area (Dingel & Neiman, 2020).
 OECD (2020)
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://www.oecd.org/coronavirus/policy-responses/capacity-for-remote-working-can-affect-lockdown-costs-differently-across-places-0e85740e/"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 og https://voxeu.org/article/potential-remote-working-across-different-places?fb
clid=IwAR2zo04l-Hdlz9Tn2fCRCs4itnG7rI4_SwjenBl4XK5nWUi2Y35yzCdQmmo
\end_layout

\end_inset

 apply this classification to data from labour force surveys in 27 EU countries,
 Switzerland, Turkey and the US.
 They find, that cities generally have a larger share of employment in occupatio
ns that can work from home and estimate, that 40 pct.
 of Danish jobs can potentially be performed remotely on the national level,
 whereas the number is around 47 pct.
 of jobs in the Copenhagen area.
 OECD (2020) also provide an interesting point, that while big cities may
 suffer from a higher risk of fast spread of a disease like COVID-19 because
 of high population density, a greater potential for working from home can
 provide a source of resilience to the economic downturn following the COVID-19
 crisis (OECD, 2020).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In line with the referenced studies, most of the literature on remote work
 focus on the supply side of the labour market by surveying employees about
 their perspectives on working remotely.
 However, in order for remote work to become widespread, the expectations
 of both employers and employees must match.
 Job listings are interesting because they shed light on the demand side
 of the labour market, ie.
 the employer, and their perception on whether a job can be performed remotely.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
New methods for obtaining text data such as job postings create new ways
 to do data analysis.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method of obtaining text data by websraping is a relatively new tool,
 but it can be powerful in gaining insight into formerly inaccessibe data
 sources.
 As an example, management consultants in Denmark have used text data from
 job postings to generate descriptive statistics about the development of
 demand in labour within the two industries IT and telecommunications and
 and the iron, metal and auto sectors
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://www.hbseconomics.dk/publications/analysis-of-labour-demand-using-job-posti
ngs/?fbclid=IwAR0VGB0_9mB7hLlhC77m8wzh_TO2Y2OO9JkRFMOfPCBDZZl1Y98Pw4X-Fkg
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
eller Højbjerre Brauer Schultz (2016): "Analyse af arbejdskraftefterspørgslen
 ved hjælp af jobopslag".
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Other projects include feeding job descriptions to a machine learning model
 to estimate appropriate salary
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://www.datascienceretreat.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/Salary-Prediction.pdf.
 Note that this type of analysis requires job posting data including a salary
 level.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To our best knowledge, there does not currently exist analysis of the remote
 labour market in Denmark using data from job postings.
 Thus, this paper's contribution is to complement the picture of the remote
 labour market which has already been painted by previous research with
 the insights from the Danish labor market.
 The descriptive analysis confirms what media outlets and academics have
 foreseen; the option of working remotely is becoming increasingly available,
 and global pandemic seems to have created a wave for workplaces to ride
 on with.
 The potential for remote work is dependant on the composition of the labour
 market and the skill level of the labor force, and may also require workplaces
 to formalize policies or guidelines for remote work to be a success in
 the long run.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
smallskip
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rest of the paper is structured as follows: Section 2 describes the
 data collection and cleaning proces and results from sample controls.
 Section 3 is a descriptive analysis of the remote labour market in Denmark
 including a text analysis of the job titles and descriptions.
 Section 4 explains theory and methods for forecasting, followed by a forecastin
g of the remote labour market in absence of COVID-19 in Section 5.
 Section 6 discusses results, strenghts and weaknesses, further research
 on this topis and ends with a conclusion on the project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Theory and methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Data collection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For this project, we will scrape job listings from the Danish job portal
 Jobindex in the period 2015-2020.
 More specifically, we will scrape the job title, company, and a preview
 of the full job listing.
 These are all available on the search results page (see Figure 1).
 Ideally, we would have liked to scrape the full job listing.
 However, doing so would require scraping not only Jobindex but also different
 company websites and PDF with varying HTML structure and although we wrote
 a program for this, running it would take more time than what we had available
 for the project.
 It is due to these same time constraints that we decided not to extend
 the period sample any further.
\end_layout

